The '''Action of 8 May 1941''' was a [[single ship action]] fought during the [[Second World War]] by the [[Royal Navy|British]] [[heavy cruiser]] {{HMS|Cornwall|56|6}} and the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' (German Navy) [[auxiliary cruiser]] {{Ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Pinguin||2}}/{{lang|de|Schiff 33}} (Raider F to the [[Admiralty]]). The engagement took place in the [[Indian Ocean]] off the [[Seychelles]] archipelago, north of [[Madagascar]]. ''Pinguin'' caused slight damage to ''Cornwall'', before its fire on ''Pinguin'' caused an explosion and sank it.

A British sailor was killed and about {{circa|200}} of the {{nowrap|222 British}} and Indian [[Merchant Navy (United Kingdom)|Merchant Navy]] prisoners on ''Pinguin'', captured from over thirty merchant vessels, were also killed. Of the crew of {{nowrap|401 men,}} {{nowrap|323 were}} killed and {{nowrap|60 were}} rescued along with {{nowrap|22 of}} the Merchant Navy prisoners. ''Cornwall'' returned to [[Durban]] for repairs until 10 June.

==Background==
===HMS ''Cornwall''===

''Cornwall'' (Captain [[P. C. W. Manwaring]]) was a {{sclass2-|County|cruiser|0}} [[heavy cruiser]] of the ''Kent'' subclass, built in the mid-1920s. It had a displacement of {{convert|10000|LT|t|abbr=on}}, carried eight {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on}} guns in four twin turrets, four {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft guns]] in two twin turrets, two four-barrel [[QF 2-pounder naval gun|2-pounder pom-pom]] guns and two {{convert|.50|in|mm|1|abbr=on}} [[machine gun]]s. ''Cornwall'' had an aircraft catapult, three [[Supermarine Walrus]] [[amphibious aircraft]] and had a maximum speed of {{convert|31.5|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Forzyk|Palmer|2010|p=58}}{{sfn|Roskill|1957|p=578}}

===''Pinguin''===

{{main|German auxiliary cruiser Pinguin|l1=German auxiliary cruiser ''Pinguin''}}

The auxiliary cruiser ''Pinguin'' ([[Captain (naval)|Captain]] [[Ernst-Felix Krüder]]), was originally the [[cargo ship|freighter]] ''Kandelfels'', which had been launched in 1936. After conversion to an auxiliary cruiser it became {{lang|de|Schiff 33}} to the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]''. ''Pinguin'' was armed with six {{convert|150|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, a {{convert|75|mm|in|abbr=on}} gun, two {{convert|37|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} anti-aircraft guns, four {{convert|20|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} [[autocannon]], two [[torpedo tube]]s, 300 [[Naval mine|mines]] and an [[Arado Ar 196]] A-1 [[floatplane]].{{sfn|Roskill|1957|p=604}} By 15 January, ''Pinguin'' (''Raider F'' to the British) had {{nowrap|captured 14}} [[Norway|Norwegian]] merchant vessels by [[commerce raiding]]. It had captured three {{convert|12000|LT|t|abbr=on}} [[factory ship]]s and 11 [[whaler]]s belonging to the same whaling company. The prizes were sent to Occupied [[France]] where one was renamed {{Ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Adjutant||2}} and was used as minelayer for the German raiders in the South Atlantic and the Indian Ocean. In April, ''Pinguin'' sank three British merchant ships in the Indian Ocean, close to the [[Equator]].{{sfn|Roskill|1957|pp=367, 384}}

==Prelude==

{{imageframe
|width=220
|caption= {{centre|Cape Guardafui}}
|content=
{{Superimpose
