|x            = 116
|y            = 99
}} }}

After sinking ''Clan Buchanan'' on 28 April, ''Pinguin'' sailed north-west and on 4 May, fuelled and provisioned ''Adjutant'', which was sent away to wait at a rendezvous near the [[Saya de Malha Bank]]. Just after {{nowrap|5:00 a.m.}} on 7 May, ''Pinguin'' intercepted and sank the {{convert|3663|LT|t}} tanker ''British Emperor'', which was on passage from Durban to Abadan, about {{convert|375|nmi|abbr=on}} east-south-east of [[Cape Guardafui]]. ''Emperor'' had sent a distress message and ''Cornwall'', en route to refuel at the [[Seychelles]] Islands intercepted the message, when about {{convert|520|nmi|abbr=on}} south of the attack. ''Cornwall'' altered course to north-north-west and increased speed to {{convert|20|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}. A plan was devised to catch the raider, using the Walrus spotter aircraft carried by ''Cornwall'' to close the raider's ''furthest on'' line and then search to cover the largest potential variations of the raiding ship's speed and course.{{sfn|Forzyk|Palmer|2010|p=58}}

''Cornwall'' increased speed to {{convert|25.5|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}, heading north between the Seychelles and the [[Chagos Archipelago]].{{sfn|Waters|2016|pp=107–108}} Vice-Admiral [[Ralph Leatham]] the Commander-in-Chief [[East Indies Station]], ordered other ships to participate in the search. {{HMNZS|Leander}} was sailing westwards at {{convert|25|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} from [[Nine Degree Channel]] towards [[Socotra]], while {{HMS|Liverpool|C11|6}}, which was north of Cape Guardafui, sailed for [[Maliku Kandu|Eight Degree Channel]], making for [[Colombo]]. {{HMS|Glasgow|C21|6}}, steaming from the [[Gulf of Aden]], passed Cape Guardafui that morning at {{convert|23|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}, to a position about {{convert|100|nmi|abbr=on}} south-east of the headland. The ship then turned south-west at {{convert|20|kn|mph+km/h|abbr=on}} towards the Equator, about {{convert|300|nmi|abbr=on}} from the African coast. Farther west, the [[armed merchant cruiser]] {{HMS|Hector|F45|6}}, patrolled from the Equator to a position {{convert|300|nmi|abbr=on}} to the south-west.{{sfn|Waters|2016|p=108}}

On the afternoon of 7 May, the two aircraft on ''Cornwall'' flew reconnaissance sorties for three hours and then altered course to get on the line of the main ''Vignot'' search. This was plotted for a mean speed of {{convert|13|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} for an hour after the time of the raider report, assuming that the raider needed an hour to sink ''British Emperor'' and then depart at full speed until dark. At {{nowrap|9:30 p.m.,}} ''Cornwall'' turned east-south-east and slowed to search on this line, before the moon set. At dawn, ''Cornwall'' sent both aircraft to search an area three knots on either side of the raider's estimated speed and turned east at {{convert|18|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} (steaming away from the raider). At {{nowrap|7:07 a.m.}} on 8 May, one of the aircraft sighted a ship heading south-west at {{convert|13|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}, about {{convert|65|nmi|abbr=on}} west of ''Cornwall'' but did not report the sighting, until landing at about {{nowrap|8:00 a.m.}} At {{nowrap|8:25 a.m.,}} ''Cornwall'' altered course to about west-by-south and increased speed to {{convert|23|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}. The second aircraft was launched again at {{nowrap|10:15 a.m.}} and at {{nowrap|12:23 p.m.}} it reported that the unknown ship was steaming at {{convert|15|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} and had hoisted the signal letters of a Norwegian motor-vessel ''Tamerlane'', which the raider resembled but was not on the list of expected ships.{{sfn|Waters|2016|pp=108–109}}

==Battle==

[[File:HMS Cornwall (56).jpg|thumb|left|{{centre|HMS ''Cornwall'' in 1929}}]]
''Cornwall'' increased speed to {{convert|26|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} then to {{convert|28|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}}. At {{nowrap|1:45 p.m.,}} an aircraft was launched to give the bearing, course and speed of the suspected ship by wireless; the ship became visible from ''Cornwall'' at {{nowrap|4:07 p.m.}} The ship began transmitting ''raider reports'', claiming to be ''Tamerlane''. Despite orders to heave-to and two warning shots, the ship maintained course and speed for more than an hour, until the range was fewer than {{convert|12000|yd|m|abbr=on}} yards. At {{nowrap|5:10 p.m.,}} ''Cornwall'' turned to port and the suspected raider made a larger turn to port, opening fire with five guns just before {{nowrap|5:15 p.m.}}{{sfn|Waters|2016|p=109}}

Due to mechanical failures, ''Cornwall'' did not return fire for about two minutes and was frequently straddled by shells fired at a rapid rate, before firing two salvoes from the forward {{nowrap|8-inch turrets.}} The fore steering gear of ''Cornwall'' was disabled by a {{nowrap|5.9-inch}} shell hit and after going out of control for a moment, the after steering gear used. By {{nowrap|5:18 p.m.,}} all of ''Cornwall's'' guns had opened fire, with the advantage of superior range finders and director [[fire-control system]]s, instead of local gun control. A salvo hit ''Pinguin'', which blew up at {{nowrap|5:26 p.m.}} and sank {{convert|500|nmi|abbr=on}} north of the Seychelles, about {{convert|300|nmi|abbr=on}} from where it had sunk ''British Emperor''.{{sfn|Waters|2016|p=109}}

==Aftermath==
===Analysis===
The commerce-raiding voyage of the ''Pinguin'' had lasted from 22 June 1940 – 8 May 1941 and the ship sank or captured {{nowrap|28 ships}} of {{nowrap|136,642 [[Gross register tonnage|GRT]].}} About {{nowrap|50,000 GRT}} of shipping was sent to Germany as [[Prize (law)|prizes]]. ''Cornwall'' returned to [[Durban]] for repairs until 10 June; the tactics of the captain of ''Cornwall'' in shadowing, attempted to identify and closing with ''Pinguin'' was criticised by the Admiralty. The crew of ''Pinguin'' had been skilful in disguising the ship and it was difficult to approach a suspicious, yet unidentified ship. A raider had the tactical advantage in deciding when to open fire, before it was unmasked and investigating ships courted danger, if the vessel approached from a direction favourable to a raider's guns and torpedoes. Allied ships were given secret call-signs and a system was devised for the investigating ship to refer to the Admiralty by wireless to verify ship identities. The new methods made ship identification much easier but took months to implement and similar events occurred, when ships were either allowed to sail on and turned out to be raiders or were  intercepted and sprang a surprise on the British warship.{{sfn|Roskill|1957|p=385}}


[[File:HMS Bermuda aircraft.jpg|thumb|left|{{centre|Example of a Walrus amphibian being catapulted from a cruiser ({{HMS|Bermuda|52|6}})}}]]
The success against ''Pinguin'' and other raiders was due to the navy Operational Intelligence Centre (OIC) of the [[Naval Intelligence Division]], at the Admiralty. The OIC tracked raiders, based on the position of the sinking of Allied merchant ships and by collating rare sightings and distress signals. German commerce-raiders kept radio silence, avoided common shipping routes, searching for independently routed vessels and tried to prevent their victims from transmitting wireless messages. From May to November 1941, the Germans lost ''Pinguin'' and two more commerce-raiders but [[Enigma machine|Enigma]] decrypts by the [[Government Communications Headquarters|Government Code and Cypher School]] (GC&CS) was only involved in one sinking.{{sfn|Hinsley|1994|pp=126–127, 197}}

German commerce-raiders used the {{lang|de|Heimische Gewässer}} (Home Waters) Enigma settings, known as ''Dolphin'' to the British, before departing and when returning to Germany. The seven raiders at sea in May 1941 had sailed in 1940, before Enigma intelligence became available to the British. When at sea, Enigma-equipped raiders used the {{lang|de|Ausserheimisch}} settings if they broke radio silence, which [[Hut 4]] at [[Bletchley Park]] never managed to penetrate. ''Atlantis'', the third raider lost in 1941, was sunk by {{HMS|Devonshire|39|6}} on 22 November after the British read U-boat signals in the {{lang|de|Heimische Gewässer}} setting, introduced in October 1941, to arrange a re-fuelling rendezvous.{{sfn|Hinsley|1994|pp=126–127, 197}}

===Casualties===
A British sailor near to the stern of ''Cornwall'' was killed when ''Pinguin'' opened fire. Among the men on ''Pinguin'' were {{nowrap|222 British}} and Indian merchant sailors, captured from over thirty merchant vessels. Of the crew of {{nowrap|401 men,}} the captain and {{nowrap|322 others}} were killed and {{nowrap|60 were}} rescued, along with {{nowrap|22 of}} the Merchant Navy prisoners.{{sfn|Rohwer|Hümmelchen|1992|p=62}}

